      "comment_id" : 131691378,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "Very, very good answer. But, just for the clarity of options here: <code>@JsonProperty(access = Access.WRITE_ONLY) private String securityCode;</code> can then as well be <code>@JsonProperty(access = Access.WRITE_ONLY) public String securityCode;</code>."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9120249,
      "reputation" : 16772,
      "user_id" : 6785908,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 70,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cbe492468c7ba6f2dd121915dc9d6634?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "so-random-dude",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6785908/so-random-dude"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 28,
    "last_activity_date" : 1760107768,
    "last_edit_date" : 1760107768,
    "creation_date" : 1495658818,
    "answer_id" : 44168171,
    "question_id" : 14708386,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Adding this here because somebody else may search this again in future, like me. This Answer is an extension to the <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/14708961/6785908\">Accepted Answer</a></p>\n<p>You have two options:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><p>Jackson works on setters-getters of fields. So, you can just remove getter of field which you want to omit in JSON. (If you don't need getter at other place.)</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Or, you can use the <code>@JsonIgnore</code> <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/14708961/6785908\">annotation of Jackson</a> on getter method of that field and you see there in no such key-value pair in resulted JSON.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<pre><code>@JsonIgnore\npublic int getSecurityCode(){\n    return securityCode;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Actually, <strong>newer version of Jackson added READ_ONLY and WRITE_ONLY annotation arguments for JsonProperty</strong>. So you could also do something like this.</p>\n<pre><code>@JsonProperty(access = Access.WRITE_ONLY)\nprivate String securityCode;\n</code></pre>\n<p>instead of</p>\n<pre><code>@JsonIgnore\npublic int getSecurityCode(){\n  return securityCode;\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 15519327,
      "reputation" : 21,
      "user_id" : 11195939,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e68d3aa589097c4aec29e4a1d1f8d560?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Puneet",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/11195939/puneet"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1561141494,
    "last_edit_date" : 1561141494,
    "creation_date" : 1561130630,
    "answer_id" : 56706291,
    "question_id" : 14708386,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I had a similar case where I needed some property to be deserialized (JSON to Object) but not serialized (Object to JSON)</p>\n\n<p>First i went for <code>@JsonIgnore</code> - it did prevent serialization of unwanted property, but failed to de-serialize it too. Trying <code>value</code> attribute didn't help either as it requires some condition.</p>\n\n<p>Finally, working <code>@JsonProperty</code> with <code>access</code> attribute worked like a charm.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2204985,
      "reputation" : 1250,
      "user_id" : 1948438,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/aade09a6fae8bf51c14c71ddb8f9469c?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "CamelTM",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1948438/cameltm"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1561132197,
    "creation_date" : 1561132197,
    "answer_id" : 56706735,
    "question_id" : 14708386,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Field Level:</p>\n\n<pre><code>public class User {\n    private String name;\n    private int age;\n    @JsonIgnore\n    private int securityCode;\n\n    // getters and setters\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Class Level:</p>\n\n<pre><code>@JsonIgnoreProperties(value = { \"securityCode\" })\npublic class User {\n    private String name;\n    private int age;\n    private int securityCode;\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 10747673,
      "reputation" : 605,
      "user_id" : 7908330,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/JqYnb.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Arnoldkk",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7908330/arnoldkk"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1644480789,
    "creation_date" : 1644480789,
    "answer_id" : 71061718,
    "question_id" : 14708386,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I suggest you use this.</p>\n<pre><code>   @JsonProperty(access = JsonProperty.Access.WRITE_ONLY)\n   private int securityCode;\n</code></pre>\n<p>This allows you to set the value of securityCode(especially if you use lombok @Setter) and also prevent the field from showing up in the GET request.</p>\n"
  } ],
